Ca 1200":"circa 1200","1165":"1165","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1230":"1230","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1269":"1269","1203":"1203","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1218":"1218","Clinge, Zeeland, Nederland":"Clinge, Zeeland, Nederland"},"en":{"1165–":"1165–Deceased","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1163–1265":"1163–1265","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1160–1218":"1160–1218","1200–1269":"1200–1269","1120–1179":"1120–1179","1131–1179":"1131–1179","Ca 1200":"about 1200","1165":"1165","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1230":"1230","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1269":"1269","1203":"1203","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1218":"1218","Clinge, Zeeland, Nederland":"Clinge, Zeeland, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Oda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Rhoda ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Oda Van Beveren van Pumbeke was born in 1165, in Clinge, Zeeland, Netherlands, her father, Jordaan van Beveren, was 45 and her mother, Badeloga or Badeloch van Breda or van Voorne, was 35. She had at least 1 son with Wulfard van Maelstede."},"et":{"1165–":"1165–Surnud","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1163–1265":"1163–1265","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1160–1218":"1160–1218","1200–1269":"1200–1269","1120–1179":"1120–1179","1131–1179":"1131–1179","Ca 1200":"umbes 1200","1165":"1165","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1230":"1230","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1269":"1269","1203":"1203","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1218":"1218","Clinge, Zeeland, Nederland":"Clinge, Zeeland, Madalmaad"},"fi":{"1165–":"1165–Kuollut","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1163–1265":"1163–1265","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1160–1218":"1160–1218","1200–1269":"1200–1269","1120–1179":"1120–1179","1131–1179":"1131–1179","Ca 1200":"noin 1200","1165":"1165","1131":"1131","1120":"1120","1230":"1230","1163":"1163","1152":"1152","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1269":"1269","1203":"1203","1179":"1179","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1218":"1218","Clinge, Zeeland, Nederland":"Clinge, Zeeland, Alankomaat"},"fr":{"1165–":"1165–Décédée","1152–1203":"1152–1203","1163–1265":"1163–1265","1165–Female":"1165–Décédée","1170–1230":"1170–1230","11